  {
    "title": "Network Diagrams",
    "description": "Network visualizations",
    "plots": [
      {
        "plot": "adjacencymatrix1.json",
        "thumbnail": "adjacencymatrix1_raytrace_640x360.jpg",
        "image": "adjacencymatrix1_raytrace_3840x2160.jpg",
        "title": "Adjacency Matrix",
        "description": "An adjacency matrix showing character co-occurrence in Les Misérables",
        "notes": "<p>This visualization shows character relationships in Victor Hugo's novel, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_Mis%C3%A9rables\">Les Misérables</a>. The data is a network, where nodes represent characters in the novel, and edges represent two characters appearing in the same chapter. While this data can be drawn as a node-link graph, this chart is an adjacency matrix. Since co-occurrences are not directed, the chart is symmetrical. The characters are ordered according to a clustering algorithm which detects character communities, rather than alphabetically, or by total co-occurrences.</p><p>Data linked from <a href=\"https://github.com/vega/vega-datasets\">vega-datasets</a>.</p><p><a href=\"https://www-cs-faculty.stanford.edu/~knuth/sgb.html\">D. E. Knuth, The Stanford GraphBase: A Platform for Combinatorial Computing, Addison-Wesley, Reading, MA (1993)</a>.</p>"
      },
      {
